title: For Sale:  Colt R6830 Lightweight 7.62x39 Like NEW
postcontent:
This is a RARE opportunity to own a special Colt AR. Under present circumstances perhaps an even better time to act.

Not only is this Colt a rarity in its caliber - 7.62x39, it is in near new condition, but without box, manual, or goodie bag. The firearm has been well kept and was purchased "like new" as a bare gun in the early 90s by the owner I bought it from. A replacement trigger group had been installed and the original was since lost.

This very meticulous 2nd owner removed the Colt carry handle upper, put it away, and replaced it with a flat top (PWS?), put in an accuwedge, changed out the flash suppressor and fired a few rounds now and then with it. He also told me up front his flat top upper would not chamber steel case or poly coated cartridges. Brass was all he ever shot through it. When I purchased it he replaced the upper with the original, still unfired. I have the original flash, and "good guy" 5 round factory steel mag.

SInce I bought it I have exactly 40 rounds through it - also brass FMJ. 20 PMC Bronze and 20 Fiocchi. I can say that the weapon is an absolute joy to fire. The well-balanced old school Sporter design with A2 stock and carry handle, combined with the R6830 buffer spring setup make the felt recoil about a wash compared to a 5.56. (My Colt 6720 M4 shooting 62gr XM855 kicks much harder.) On its iron sights at the back of my 25 yard range this Colt is also accurate - on its first box of ammo from the beanbag it shot sub-2" groups with the PMC.

Included in the sale are some very rare accessories. In addition to the beautiful rifle I am including 4 high capacity magazines: two 20 rd, one 30 round, and the 75 rd drum. No markings but I believe these to be early USA "frankenmags". (This refers to "obvious" grafting the AR15 upper mag body to the AK47 lower.) I have not tested these for cycling but they are in very good to excellent condition. A magazine selection like this is VERY hard to find.

Along with the rifle and mags is a VINTAGE beauty of a scope - 3x20 Colt 1960s Japan manufacture and in near mint condition. Worth $4-500 alone, it is a nice companion piece to the rifle.

To set up the new owner I am also including 100 rds of the Fiocchi 124gr FMJ ammo.

These guns had many upgraded parts right from the factory such as Millett sights, and Pachmayr/LAR grips, ambidextrous safety, as well as other upgrades. The DoubleStar DS-4 Carbine AR-15 / M4 rifle was modeled as a civilian version of the military M-4. DoubleStar Corp’s Origin
Many people ask “where did DSC come from?” After 25 years of success with J&T Distributing selling black rifle parts and accessories, Teresa and Jesse Starnes (Double-Starnes’) created a full line of complete weapons to satisfy the thousands of requests to build an AR-15. The J&T Distributing customer base demanded a rifle that incorporated the versatility and quality that J&T had been providing them for so long.

Differences in AR-15 type rifles?
Some general info provided by an FFL that specializes in black guns...
USGI and/or mil-spec.: 
Commercial parts are made by casting and stamping, which requires weaker, softer steel to do. Parts wear out faster. USGI and mil-spec are forged and milled, much harder steel. And commercial parts don’t always work with mil-spec if you need a replacement, whereas all mil-spec works with all mil-spec. 

The DoubleStar costs more, but it is all USGI, all mil-spec. The DS-4 is a rifle with flattop. It does not come with a rear sight. They do that due to differences in personal preference. 
The DS-4 Comes with magazine and manual. 

The DS-4 bolt and carrier are far superior to most commercial ARs. Many commercial AR vendors say they have a mil-spec bolt carrier... probably not completely. The DoubleStar is USGI, M16 blueprint (no others can say that), all parts x-rayed and particle tested. Carrier is internally lined for the bolt travel and has a chrome firing pin. 

Finish and machining on the DS is far superior to most all manufacturers, and they use a higher grade 7075 aluminum. Most commercial manufacturers use 6061 aluminum, substandard and not mil-spec. 

I can go on and on. Only the billet and really high dollar manufacturers can really even compare to DoubleStar… And if I was to stake my life on it, I would want it to be the DoubleStar…

title: For Sale:  Sten MK3 Parts Kit and Indianapolis Ordnance Semi-Auto kit
postcontent:
This is not a gun or frearm and does not require an FFL for shipping.

Original WWII British Sten Mk 3 parts kit.  This is a parts kit that has been saw-demilled and cannot be reassembled into a working firearm, and so it has been classified as a non-firearm by the BATFE.  These parts were hand-selected for minimal wear and abuse.  All parts are included except the missing chunks of the receiver tube.  Original gun was demilled and packed in Cosmoline after the war, and is thus well preserved and rust free.

The other parts included are a premium Indianapolis Ordnance Semi-Auto parts kit, all new parts, including an 80% completed receiver tube, 16-inch barrel (required by the BATFE), semi-auto bolt and the various pins, springs, rivets, and small parts required to complete the kit.  To be very clear, the new receiver tube CANNOT BE USED WITH THE ORIGINAL BOLT.  It is designed with a vertical magazine mount and has ventilation holes already drilled.  The bolt kit is for a vertical magazine mount and is designed to fit the receiver tube.  The receiver tube has a plan decal attached for ease of use.  Instructions are included.

I bught these parts with the intention of doing the disassembly of teh Sten and building a semi-auto Sten based on the 80% receiver, which is of course perfectly legal.  Then I realized I don't have the time to complete it so I'm taking a bit of a loss to get the parts out of my project to-do list.  If you have time to do it, this would be a great project.

I can ship in the 50 US States (shipping extra, please pay the total by US Postal MO and I'll ship when it clears) or local pickup in the Tampa area (cash payment OK) is great.
